{"title_page": "Hall High School (Connecticut)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox school\n|name                = William H. Hall High School\n|image               =\n|imagesize           = \n|motto               = 'Live like a Warrior!'\n|streetaddress       = 975 North Main Street\n|city                = [[West Hartford, Connecticut|West Hartford]]\n|state               = [[Connecticut]]\n|zipcode             = 06117\n|country             = [[United States]]\n|district            = [[West Hartford Public Schools]]\n|established         = 1924<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web |url=https://patch.com/connecticut/westhartford/what-year-was-this-team-picture-taken |title=What Year Was this Team Picture Taken? |last=Newton |first=Ronni |date=April 30, 2012 |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n|coordinates         = {{coord|41.7946|-72.7513|display=inline,title}}\n|type                = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]] [[high school]]\n|principal           = Dan Zittoun\n|superintendent      = Tom Moore\n|grades              = [[Ninth grade|9]]\u2013[[Twelfth grade|12]]\n|campus              =\n|founder             = William H. Hall\n|faculty             = 97 (2014\u201315)\n|students            = 1,447 (2016-17)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=0904920&ID=090492001015|title=Hall High School|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref>\n|team_name           = Warriors\n|colors              = Blue and White {{color box|blue}}{{color box|white}}\n|newspaper           = 'Hall Highlights'\n|yearbook            = 'Hallmarks'\n|rivals              = [[Conard High School]]\n|homepage            = [http://hall.whps.org/ Official Site]\n|footnotes           = Source:<ref name=\"us news overview\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/connecticut/districts/west-hartford-school-district/william-h-hall-high-school-4566 |title=Hall High School in West Hartford, CT |website=US News |date=2017 |accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> except where noted\n}}\n\n'''William H. Hall High School,''' also known as '''Hall High''', is a four-year public [[high school]] located in [[West Hartford, Connecticut|West Hartford]], in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Connecticut]]. Opened in 1924, it was named after William Henry Hall, who was a teacher, principal, and superintendent of schools in West Hartford.<ref name=\"history\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whps.org/uploaded/Schools/High_Schools/Hall_High_School/Students/2017-2018_William_H._Hall_High_School_Student_Handbook_-_Final.pdf?1503332266992 |title=William H. Hall High School Student Handbook 2017\u20132018 |accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> The school colors are [[blue]] and [[white (color)|white]], and the mascot is the \"Warrior\". It is one of two public high schools in the [[West Hartford Public Schools]], the other being [[Conard High School]]. Enrollment in grades 9\u201312 for the 2014\u20132015 school year was 1,437 students.<ref name=\"us news overview\"/>\n\n== Demographics ==\nThe 2014\u20132015 demographic profile is as follows: White 65%, Hispanic 12%, Asian American 10%, Black 10%, two or more races 3%, American Indian/Alaskan Native 1%, and Hawaiian Native/Pacific Islander 0.1%.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/connecticut/districts/west-hartford-school-district/hall-high-school-4566/student-body |title=Hall High School Student Body |website=U.S. News & World Report |date=2017 |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics and clubs==\nIn soccer, Hall won the 1980 state championship 3-2 over [[E. O. Smith High School]]. The school also reached the semifinals of the state tournament four times under head coach Zeke Seguro, who won his 150th game as coach on October 10, 2008 with a 1-0 victory at South Windsor. In 2018, the Hall boys lost 1-0 to Glastonbury in the state championship. However, they won the 2019 state championship 3-1 over Greenwich. Hall's boys' cross country team has won the Central Connecticut Conference four of the last five years dating back to 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://centralconnecticutconference.org/index.php/championship-meets-crosscountry-b-2798 |title=Cross Country Archives: Championship Meets |website=Central Connecticut Conference |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHall's boys indoor track team won both Class LL Championships and the CT State Open Championships in 2019. {{cn|date=April 2019}}\n\nHall has a renowned jazz program, which stage an annual production called Pops <nowiki>'n' Jazz, regularly selling over 3,000 tickets every year. They have also won the Essentially Ellington High School Jazz Band Competition and Festival twice, in 1998 and 2000. The band has performed for the president at the White House, appeared in Ken Burns's documentary film ''Jazz''</nowiki> and shared the stage with countless jazz luminaries, including Count Basie Orchestra, Wynton Marsalis,  Jimmy Heath, Ted Nash, Arturo O'Farrell, Elliot Mason, John Daversa, Phil Woods and Joe Lovano.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/05/13/nyregion/not-just-another-school-band-recital.html |title=Not Just Another School Band Recital |last=Staudter |first=Thomas |date=May 13, 2001 |work=The New York Times |access-date=March 5, 2016 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Hall's chess team won the state championship.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westhartfordnews.com/news/hall-chess-team-wins-state-championship/article_76befc93-5e53-5fe4-a8e9-862b6e9f61b9.html |title=Hall Chess Team wins State Championship |date=June 23, 2011 |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Academic accomplishments==\n*[[Blue Ribbon Schools Program|Blue Ribbon School]] in 1984\u201385.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www2.ed.gov/programs/nclbbrs/list-1982.pdf |title=Archived Information: Blue Ribbon Schools Program: Schools Recognized 1982\u20131983 Through 1999\u20132002 |website=U.S. Department of Education |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n*Ranked as the 11th best school (6th best public school) in the state of Connecticut by U.S. News & World Report in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.courant.com/education/hc-best-public-high-schools-connecticut-2018-us-news-world-report-20180509-story.html |title=These Are The 15 Best Public High Schools In CT, According To U.S. News |date=9 May 2018 |website=The Hartford Courant |access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n\n<!-- Please only add notable people; see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Notability -->\n* [[Natalie Anderson (TV personality)|Natalie Anderson]], [[Survivor: San Juan Del Sur]] winner<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.kctv5.com/story/28743521/twin-reality-stars-to-help-at-the-amazing-race-casting-call |title=Twin reality stars to help at 'The Amazing Race' casting call |last=Naples |first=Kaitlyn |date=April 7, 2015 |access-date=January 17, 2018 |publisher=KCTV; Kansas City |last2=Zinni |first2=Mark}}</ref>\n*[[David Alan Basche]], actor.\n*[[Chris Carrabba]], musician and lead singer of the band [[Dashboard Confessional]] attended freshman year<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://bristolobserver.com/2015/06/26/dashboard-confessional-is-back-on-the-scene-but-focused-on-touring-first/ |title=Dashboard Confessional is back on the scene but focused on touring first |last=Chaiken |first=Mike |date=June 26, 2015 |work=Bristol Observer |access-date=January 17, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Jacob Fox]], mathematician\n*[[Joel Frahm]], jazz tenor saxophonist<ref name=\"we-ha\" />\n*[[Matthew Yang King]], actor, producer, director, and writer\n*[[Jimmy Macbride]], jazz drummer<ref name=\"we-ha\">{{cite web |url=http://we-ha.com/west-hartfords-hall-high-school-prepares-annual-pops-n-jazz/ |title=West Hartford's Hall High School Prepares for Annual Pops 'n Jazz |date=February 13, 2017 |publisher=we-ha.com |access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n*Charlie Kaufman, screenwriter, director\n*[[Brad Mehldau]], Grammy award winning jazz pianist<ref name=\"we-ha\" />\n*[[Noah Preminger]], jazz saxophonist<ref name=\"we-ha\" />\n*[[Michael Schur]], Emmy Award winning actor, television producer, and writer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcconnecticut.com/the-scene/archive/West-Hartford-Guy-Makes-Parks-and-Rec-Funny-.html|title=West Hartford Guy Behind Poehler's \"Parks & Recreation\"|work=NBC Connecticut|access-date=2018-10-10|language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Roger Sperry]], neuropsychologist and [[Nobel Prize]] laureate<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/medicine/laureates/1981/sperry-bio.html |title=Roger W. Sperry - Biographical |website=Nobelprize.org |access-date=March 12, 2016}}</ref>\n*[[David H. Steinberg]], film and television writer and producer.\n*[[Patrick Zimmerli]], composer<ref name=\"we-ha\" />\n*[[Dave Chameides]], Emmy Award winning Director and Cameraman<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0150505/|title=David Chameides|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>\n*Rob \"the Drummer\" Gottfried, motivational speaker and drummer <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://robthedrummer.com/|title=Youth Motivational Speaker {{!}} Anti Substance Abuse {{!}} Anti Bullying {{!}} Rob the Drummer|website=robthedrummer.com|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>\n*ken over\nWavy gravy\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://hall.whps.org/}}\n*[http://www.whps.org/ West Hartford Public Schools Official Site]\n\n{{Central Connecticut Conference |state=expanded}}\n{{West Hartford Public Schools}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in West Hartford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Schools in Hartford County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:1924 establishments in Connecticut]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox school\n|name                = William H. Hall High School\n|image               =\n|imagesize           = \n|motto               = 'Live like a Warrior!'\n|streetaddress       = 975 North Main Street\n|city                = [[West Hartford, Connecticut|West Hartford]]\n|state               = [[Connecticut]]\n|zipcode             = 06117\n|country             = [[United States]]\n|district            = [[West Hartford Public Schools]]\n|established         = 1924<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web |url=https://patch.com/connecticut/westhartford/what-year-was-this-team-picture-taken |title=What Year Was this Team Picture Taken? |last=Newton |first=Ronni |date=April 30, 2012 |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n|coordinates         = {{coord|41.7946|-72.7513|display=inline,title}}\n|type                = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]] [[high school]]\n|principal           = Dan Zittoun\n|superintendent      = Tom Moore\n|grades              = [[Ninth grade|9]]\u2013[[Twelfth grade|12]]\n|campus              =\n|founder             = William H. Hall\n|faculty             = 97 (2014\u201315)\n|students            = 1,447 (2016-17)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=0904920&ID=090492001015|title=Hall High School|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref>\n|team_name           = Warriors\n|colors              = Blue and White {{color box|blue}}{{color box|white}}\n|newspaper           = 'Hall Highlights'\n|yearbook            = 'Hallmarks'\n|rivals              = [[Conard High School]]\n|homepage            = [http://hall.whps.org/ Official Site]\n|footnotes           = Source:<ref name=\"us news overview\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/connecticut/districts/west-hartford-school-district/william-h-hall-high-school-4566 |title=Hall High School in West Hartford, CT |website=US News |date=2017 |accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> except where noted\n}}\n\n'''William H. Hall High School,''' also known as '''Hall High''', is a four-year public [[high school]] located in [[West Hartford, Connecticut|West Hartford]], in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Connecticut]]. Opened in 1924, it was named after William Henry Hall, who was a teacher, principal, and superintendent of schools in West Hartford.<ref name=\"history\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whps.org/uploaded/Schools/High_Schools/Hall_High_School/Students/2017-2018_William_H._Hall_High_School_Student_Handbook_-_Final.pdf?1503332266992 |title=William H. Hall High School Student Handbook 2017\u20132018 |accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> The school colors are [[blue]] and [[white (color)|white]], and the mascot is the \"Warrior\". It is one of two public high schools in the [[West Hartford Public Schools]], the other being [[Conard High School]]. Enrollment in grades 9\u201312 for the 2014\u20132015 school year was 1,437 students.<ref name=\"us news overview\"/>\n\n== Demographics ==\nThe 2014\u20132015 demographic profile is as follows: White 65%, Hispanic 12%, Asian American 10%, Black 10%, two or more races 3%, American Indian/Alaskan Native 1%, and Hawaiian Native/Pacific Islander 0.1%.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/connecticut/districts/west-hartford-school-district/hall-high-school-4566/student-body |title=Hall High School Student Body |website=U.S. News & World Report |date=2017 |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics and clubs==\nIn soccer, Hall won the 1980 state championship 3-2 over [[E. O. Smith High School]]. The school also reached the semifinals of the state tournament four times under head coach Zeke Seguro, who won his 150th game as coach on October 10, 2008 with a 1-0 victory at South Windsor. In 2018, the Hall boys lost 1-0 to Glastonbury in the state championship. However, they won the 2019 state championship 3-1 over Greenwich. Hall's boys' cross country team has won the Central Connecticut Conference four of the last five years dating back to 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://centralconnecticutconference.org/index.php/championship-meets-crosscountry-b-2798 |title=Cross Country Archives: Championship Meets |website=Central Connecticut Conference |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHall's boys indoor track team won both Class LL Championships and the CT State Open Championships in 2019. {{cn|date=April 2019}}\n\nHall has a renowned jazz program, which stage an annual production called Pops <nowiki>'n' Jazz, regularly selling over 3,000 tickets every year. They have also won the Essentially Ellington High School Jazz Band Competition and Festival twice, in 1998 and 2000. The band has performed for the president at the White House, appeared in Ken Burns's documentary film ''Jazz''</nowiki> and shared the stage with countless jazz luminaries, including Count Basie Orchestra, Wynton Marsalis,  Jimmy Heath, Ted Nash, Arturo O'Farrell, Elliot Mason, John Daversa, Phil Woods and Joe Lovano.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/05/13/nyregion/not-just-another-school-band-recital.html |title=Not Just Another School Band Recital |last=Staudter |first=Thomas |date=May 13, 2001 |work=The New York Times |access-date=March 5, 2016 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Hall's chess team won the state championship.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westhartfordnews.com/news/hall-chess-team-wins-state-championship/article_76befc93-5e53-5fe4-a8e9-862b6e9f61b9.html |title=Hall Chess Team wins State Championship |date=June 23, 2011 |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Academic accomplishments==\n*[[Blue Ribbon Schools Program|Blue Ribbon School]] in 1984\u201385.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www2.ed.gov/programs/nclbbrs/list-1982.pdf |title=Archived Information: Blue Ribbon Schools Program: Schools Recognized 1982\u20131983 Through 1999\u20132002 |website=U.S. Department of Education |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n*Ranked as the 11th best school (6th best public school) in the state of Connecticut by U.S. News & World Report in 2018.<ref>{{cite w