{"title_page": "1971 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n  |year=1971\n  |team=Western Kentucky Hilltoppers\n  |sport=football\n  |image=\n  |image_size=\n  |conference=Ohio Valley Conference\n  |division=\n  |short_conf=OVC\n  |CoachRank=\n  |APRank=6\n  |record=8\u20132\n  |conf_record=6\u20131\n  |head_coach= [[Jimmy Feix]]\n  |hc_year=4th\n  |off_coach=\n  |def_coach=\n  |off_scheme=\n  |def_scheme=\n  |stadium= [[Houchens Industries\u2013L. T. Smith Stadium|L. T. Smith Stadium]]\n  |champion= OVC champion\n  |bowl= \n  |bowl_result= \n}}\n{{1971 Ohio Valley Conference football standings}}\nThe '''1971 Western Kentucky football team''' represented [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky University]] during the [[1971 NCAA College Division football season]]. The team was led by coach [[Jimmy Feix]] and won their second consecutive [[List of Ohio Valley Conference football champions|Ohio Valley Conference]] championship and the school's fourth overall. The Hilltoppers\u2019 rankings in the final polls were UPI 12<ref>{{cite news|title=Delaware Tops Final Poll|newspaper=The Terre Haute Star|location=Terre Haute, Indiana|date=November 26, 1971|page=27|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11092275/poll_1971_1126_small_upi_final/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|access-date=May 18, 2017}}{{Open access}}</ref> and AP 6,<ref>{{cite news|title=Delaware is first|newspaper=The Courier-News|location=Bridgewater, New Jersey|date=November 24, 1971|page=41|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11092292/poll_1971_1124_small_ap_final/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|access-date=May 18, 2017}}{{Open access}}</ref> and finished ranked 1st in Pass Defense in NCAA Division II.\nThe team roster included future [[National Football League|NFL]] players [[Virgil Livers]], John Bushong, Clarence \u201cJazz\u201d Jackson, and Mike McCoy.  Jim Barber was named to the Universal Sports All-American team.  The All OVC team included Barber, Terry Kokinda, Bob Morehead, Leo Peckenpaugh, Bill Sykes, and Terry Thompson.<ref>[https://wkusports.com/documents/2019/7/17/2019_WKU_Football_Media_Guide.pdf WKU Football Media Guide retrieved 31 March 2020.]</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n| rankyear = 1971\n| poll = AP\n| rankdivision = NCAA College Division\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 18\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 15<small> ''UPI''</small>\n| opponent = [[Wittenberg Tigers football|Wittenberg]]\n| site_stadium = [[Houchens Industries\u2013L. T. Smith Stadium|L. T. Smith Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Bowling Green, KY]]\n| score = 33\u20137\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 25\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = 6\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1971|team=Austin Peay Governors|title=Austin Peay}}\n| site_stadium = [[Governors Stadium|Municipal Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Clarksville, TN]]\n| score = 46\u20137\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 2\n| w/l = w\n| rank = 4\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1971|team=East Tennessee State Buccaneers|title=East Tennessee State}}\n| site_stadium = L. T. Smith Stadium\n| site_cityst = Bowling Green, KY\n| score = 36-7\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 9\n| w/l = l\n| away = y\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 5\n| opponent = [[1971 Eastern Michigan Hurons football team|Eastern Michigan]]\n| opprank = 6\n| site_stadium = [[Rynearson Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Ypsilanti, MI]]\n| score = 14\u201317\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 16\n| w/l = w\n| rank = 10\n| homecoming = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1971|team=Tennessee Tech Golden Eagles|title=Tennessee Tech}}\n| site_stadium = L. T. Smith Stadium\n| site_cityst = Bowling Green, KY\n| score = 15\u20137\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 23\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = 10<small> ''UPI''</small>\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1971|team=Eastern Kentucky Colonels|title=Eastern Kentucky}}\n| opprank = 12