 =\n|website                =\n|footnotes              = \n}}\n\n'''Saruatha''' is a [[Village development committee (Nepal)|village development committee]] in [[Rautahat District]] in the [[Narayani Zone]] of south-eastern [[Nepal]]. At the time of the [[1991 Nepal census]] it had a population of 4463 people living in 836 individual households.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.digitalhimalaya.com/collections/nepalcensus/form.php?selection=1|title=Nepal Census 2001|work=Nepal's Village Development Committees|publisher=[[Digital Himalaya]]|accessdate=29 November 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{Rautahat District}}\n\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Rautahat District]]\n\n\n{{Narayani-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Pegship", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2013{{Narayani-geo-stub}}, +{{Province2NP-geo-stub}} usingStubSorter", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruatha"}
{"title_page": "Ray Boyle", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Raymond C. \"Ray\" Boyle<br>formerly known as Dirk London\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| imagesize   = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1925|6|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Lisbon, North Dakota]], U.S.\n| death_date  =\n| death_place = \n| death_cause =\n| occupation  = Actor of film and television<br>Production designer\n| yearsactive = Principally [[1952 in film|1952]]&ndash;[[1961 in television|1961]]\n| residence   = [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| birth_name  =\n| spouse      = [[Jan Shepard]] (married 1952)\n| othername   = \n| website     =\n}}\n'''Raymond C. Boyle''' (born June 28, 1925), credited as '''Ray Boyle''' or '''Dirk London''', is an [[United States|American]] [[actor]] known principally for his sporadic role as [[Morgan Earp]], the brother of [[Wyatt Earp]] in fifteen episodes of the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]/[[Desilu Productions]] [[Western (genre)|western]] [[television series]], ''[[The Life and Legend of Wyatt Earp]],'' starring [[Hugh O'Brian]] in the title role. Boyle's episodes began with \"The Assassins\" in 1956 and ended with \"The Outlaws Cry Murder\" in 1961.<ref name=imdb>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0102318/?ref_=nmbio_bio_nm|title=Ray Boyle|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=April 21, 2014}}</ref><ref name=tv>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/people/ray-boyle|title=Ray Boyle|publisher=tv.com|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBoyle appeared in several films too, including the roles of Shane in ''[[Zombies of the Stratosphere]]'' (1952), as Clung in ''[[Ride Clear of Diablo]]'' (1954), as Raymond Hamilton in ''[[Guns Don't Argue]]'' (1957), a film about the [[FBI]], as Matt in an uncredited role in ''[[The Lonely Man]]'' (1957), as Johnny Willows in ''[[Ambush at Cimarron Pass]]'' (1958), and as Tom Olsen in ''The Purple Gang'' (1959).<ref name=imdb/><ref name=tv/><ref>[https://www.allmovie.com/artist/ray-boyle-p7854 Allmoives, Raymond C. Boyle]</ref><ref>NY Times, George Is Ready for His \u2018Seven Year Itch\u2019, By Chris Chase, April 9, 1972</ref><ref>[https://www.filmsite.org/zombiefilms2.html filmsite.org, Greatest Zombie Films 1930s - 1950s, Zombies of the Stratosphere]</ref>\n\nHis other television roles include two 1954 episodes of the western [[anthology series]], ''[[Death Valley Days]]'', narrated by [[Stanley Andrews]], where he work with is future wife, \t[[Jan Shepard]]. He was cast in \"Bucket of Sand\" (1956) and \"The Beach Pounders\" (1957) of the military drama ''[[Navy Log]]''. In 1956 and 1957, he was cast in different roles in five episodes of another anthology series, ''[[Robert Montgomery Presents]]''. In 1957, he was cast in the episode \"Streamlined Rustlers\" of the western series ''[[Tales of the Texas Rangers]]'', starring [[Willard Parker]] and [[Harry Lauter]]. That same year he played Prader in the episode \"Conscript\" of the [[American Civil war]] drama series, ''[[The Gray Ghost (TV series)|The Gray Ghost]]'', starring [[Tod Andrews]] as [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] [[Major]] [[John Singleton Mosby]].<ref name=imdb/> In 1950s he was on the [[Hallmark Hall of Fame]], the [[Kraft Television Theatre]], [[The Big Story (radio and TV series)|The Big Story]], [[Omnibus (American TV program)|Omnibus]], [[The Mickey Rooney Show]], [[The Web (1950 TV series)|The Web]], [[Danger (TV series)|Danger]] and [[Studio One (American TV series)|Studio One]] TV shows. <ref name=tv/>\n\nFrom 1956 to 1959, he was cast in three episodes of [[Broderick Crawford]]'s [[Television syndication|syndicated]] television series, ''[[Highway Patrol (U.S. TV series)|Highway Patrol]]''. In 1958, he guest starred in an episode of the adventure series, ''[[Harbor Command]]''. Twice, in 1955 and again in 1960, he was cast in two half-hour episodes of the [[CBS]] western series, ''[[Gunsmoke]]'', starring [[James Arness]]. He was cast as Johnny in the 1960 episode \"So Dim the Light\" of the CBS anthology series, ''[[The June Allyson Show]]''.<ref name=imdb/>\n\nHe also was cast in an episode of Sergeant Preston of the Yukon with his wife Jan Shepard titled \"Eye of Evil\" in 1956.\n\nAfter ''The Life and Legend of Wyatt Earp'' ended, Boyle had one television role remaining, as Neil Gilbert in \"The Case of the Roving River\" (1961) of the CBS [[legal drama]], ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'', starring [[Raymond Burr]]. Years later in 1994 and 1995, he made single appearances each in ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'' and ''[[Beverly Hills, 90210]]''.<ref name=imdb/> On February 1, 1996 he played Benny on [[Night Stand with Dick Dietrick]].<ref name=tv/>\n\nAfter his acting ended, he worked as a production designer.<ref name=imdb/><ref>The Ear of the Heart: An Actress' Journey from Hollywood to Holy Vows, By Hart, Mother Dolores O.S.B.</ref>\n\n{{Portal|Los Angeles|California|Film|Television}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0102318}}\n* {{IBDB name|110019}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boyle, Ray}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:People from Los Angeles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Raymond C. \"Ray\" Boyle<br>formerly known as Dirk London\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| imagesize   = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1925|6|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Lisbon, North Dakota]], U.S.\n| death_date  =\n| death_place = \n| death_cause =\n| occupation  = Actor of film and television<br>Production designer\n| yearsactive = Principally [[1952 in film|1952]]&ndash;[[1961 in television|1961]]\n| residence   = [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| birth_name  =\n| spouse      = [[Jan Shepard]] (married 1952)\n| othername   = \n| website     =\n}}\n'''Raymond C. Boyle''' (born June 28, 1925), credited as '''Ray Boyle''' or '''Dirk London''', is an [[United States|American]] [[actor]] known principally for his sporadic role as [[Morgan Earp]], the brother of [[Wyatt Earp]] in fifteen episodes of the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]/[[Desilu Productions]] [[Western (genre)|western]] [[television series]], ''[[The Life and Legend of Wyatt Earp]],'' starring [[Hugh O'Brian]] in the title role. Boyle's episodes began with \"The Assassins\" in 1956 and ended with \"The Outlaws Cry Murder\" in 1961.<ref name=imdb>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0102318/?ref_=nmbio_bio_nm|title=Ray Boyle|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=April 21, 2014}}</ref><ref name=tv>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/people/ray-boyle|title=Ray Boyle|publisher=tv.com|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBoyle appeared in several films too, including the roles of Shane in ''[[Zombies of the Stratosphere]]'' (1952), as Clung in ''[[Ride Clear of Diablo]]'' (1954), as Raymond Hamilton in ''[[Guns Don't Argue]]'' (1957), a film about the [[FBI]], as Matt in an uncredited role in ''[[The Lonely Man]]'' (1957), as Johnny Willows in ''[[Ambush at Cimarron Pass]]'' (1958), and as Tom Olsen in ''The Purple Gang'' (1959).<ref name=imdb/><ref name=tv/><ref>[https://www.allmovie.com/artist/ray-boyle-p7854 Allmoives, Raymond C. Boyle]</ref><ref>NY Times, George Is Ready for His \u2018Seven Year Itch\u2019, By Chris Chase, April 9, 1972</ref><ref>[https://www.filmsite.org/zombiefilms2.html filmsite.org, Greatest Zombie Films 1930s - 1950s, Zombies of the Stratosphere]</ref>\n\nHis other television roles include two 1954 episodes of the western [[anthology series]], ''[[Death Valley Days]]'', narrated by [[Stanley Andrews]]. He was cast in \"Bucket of Sand\" (1956) and \"The Beach Pounders\" (1957) of the military drama ''[[Navy Log]]''. In 1956 and 1957, he was cast in different roles in five episodes of another anthology series, ''[[Robert Montgomery Presents]]''. In 1957, he was cast in the episode \"Streamlined Rustlers\" of the western series ''[[Tales of the Texas Rangers]]'', starring [[Willard Parker]] and [[Harry Lauter]]. That same year he played Prader in the episode \"Conscript\" of the [[American Civil war]] drama series, ''[[The Gray Ghost (TV series)|The Gray Ghost]]'', starring [[Tod Andrews]] as [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] [[Major]] [[John Singleton Mosby]].<ref name=imdb/> In 1950s he was on the [[Hallmark Hall of Fame]], the [[Kraft Television Theatre]], [[The Big Story (radio and TV series)|The Big Story]], [[Omnibus (American TV program)|Omnibus]], [[The Mickey Rooney Show]], [[The Web (1950 TV series)|The Web]], [[Danger (TV series)|Danger]] and [[Studio One (American TV series)|Studio One]] TV shows. <ref name=tv/>\n\nFrom 1956 to 1959, he was cast in three episodes of [[Broderick Crawford]]'s [[Television syndication|syndicated]] television series, ''[[Highway Patrol (U.S. TV series)|Highway Patrol]]''. In 1958, he guest starred in an episode of the adventure series, ''[[Harbor Command]]''. Twice, in 1955 and again in 1960, he was cast in two half-hour episodes of the [[CBS]] western series, ''[[Gunsmoke]]'', starring [[James Arness]]. He was cast as Johnny in the 1960 episode \"So Dim the Light\" of the CBS anthology series, ''[[The June Allyson Show]]''.<ref name=imdb/>\n\nHe also was cast in an episode of Sergeant Preston of the Yukon with his wife Jan Shepard titled \"Eye of Evil\" in 1956.\n\nAfter ''The Life and Legend of Wyatt Earp'' ended, Boyle had one television role remaining, as Neil Gilbert in \"The Case of the Roving River\" (1961) of the CBS [[legal drama]], ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'', starring [[Raymond Burr]]. Years later in 1994 and 1995, he made single appearances each in ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'' and ''[[Beverly Hills, 90210]]''.<ref name=imdb/> On February 1, 1996 he played Benny on [[Night Stand with Dick Dietrick]].<ref name=tv/>\n\nAfter his acting ended, he worked as a production designer.<ref name=imdb/><ref>The Ear of the Heart: An Actress' Journey from Hollywood to Holy Vows, By Hart, Mother Dolores O.S.B.</ref>\n\n{{Portal|Los Angeles|California|Film|Television}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0102318}}\n* {{IBDB name|110019}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boyle, Ray}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:People from Los Angeles]]\n", "name_user": "Telecineguy", "label": "safe", "comment": "Jan Shepard", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Boyle"}
{"title_page": "Toy Museum of NY", "text_new": "The '''Toy Museum of NY''' is a theatrical and performance based museum which uses the museum's collection for its performances and to tell the story of societal change. It was founded in 1999 as '''The Doll and Toy Museum of NYC''' and given its current name in 2009.<ref name=toyvb>{{cite web|title=The Toy Museum of NY|url=http://www.visitbrooklyn.org/attractions-list/the-toy-museum-of-ny|publisher=Visit Brooklyn|accessdate=2014-08-29}}</ref> Later that same year it moved from its original location in Cobble Hill to its permanent location on the second floor of [[Brooklyn Heights]]' [[St. Ann & the Holy Trinity Church]]. Among the locations for the museum's traveling locations are the Brooklyn Heights and Bay Ridge public library branches.<ref name=tmnyc>{{cite web|title=Toy Museum of New York City|url=http://www.nyc-arts.org/organizations/1679/toy-museum-of-new-york-city|website=NYC-Arts|publisher=[[Thirteen (television station)|Thirteen]]|accessdate=2014-08-29}}</ref>\n\n==Collection==\nThe museum's collection pays homage to the history of toys.  Established by Marlene Hochman, the museum is a traveling museum with performances, workshops and webinars.   In addition to rare dolls, the museum has a collection of classics like [[Mr. Potato Head]], the original Frisbee pie pan, [[G.I. Joe]] and, the [[Easy-Bake Oven]].<ref name=tmnyc/><ref name=nyt>{{cite news|last1=Etim|first1=Bassey|title=Long-Held Vision for Toy Museum Is Realized|url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/11/12/long-held-vision-for-toy-museum-is-realized/|accessdate=2014-08-29|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2009-11-12}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.toymuseumny.org/ website]\n\n{{coord missing|New York City}}\n\n[[Category:Museums established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Museums in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Toy museums in the United States]]\n\n\n{{NewYork-museum-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Toy Museum of NY''' is a theatrical and performance based museum which uses the museum's collection for its performances and to tell the story of societal change. It was founded in 1999 as '''The Doll and Toy Museum of NYC''' and given its current name in 2009.<ref name=toyvb>{{cite web|title=The Toy Museum of NY|url=http://www.visitbrooklyn.org/attractions-list/the-toy-museum-of-ny|publisher=Visit Brooklyn|accessdate=2014-08-29}}</ref> Later that samed year it moved from its original location in Cobble Hill to its permanent location on the second floor of [[Brooklyn Heights]]' [[St. Ann & the Holy Trinity Church]]. Among the locations for the museum's traveling locations are the Brooklyn Heights and Bay Ridge public library branches.<ref name=tmnyc>{{cite web|title=Toy Museum of New York City|url=http://www.nyc-arts.org/organizations/1679/toy-museum-of-new-york-city|website=NYC-Arts|publisher=[[Thirteen (television station)|Thirteen]]|accessdate=2014-08-29}}</ref>\n\n==Collection==\nThe museum's collection pays homage to the history of toys.  Established by Marlene Hochman, the museum is a traveling museum with performances, workshops and webinars.   In addition to rare dolls, the museum has a collection of classics like [[Mr. Potato Head]], the original Frisbee pie pan, [[G.I. Joe]] and, the [[Easy-Bake Oven]].<ref name=tmnyc/><ref name=nyt>{{cite news|last1=Etim|first1=Bassey|title=Long-Held Vision for Toy Museum Is Realized|url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/11/12/long-held-vision-for-toy-museum-is-realized/|accessdate=2014-08-29|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2009-11-12}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.toymuseumny.org/ website]\n\n{{coord missing|New York City}}\n\n[[Category:Museums established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Museums in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Toy museums in the United States]]\n\n\n{{NewYork-museum-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Star Mississippi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:typo (samed - same)", "url_page": "/